1
00:00:27,900 --> 00:00:30,900
Dan: I want you to quit
your post, Jake.

2
00:00:30,933 --> 00:00:33,200
I want you to take
over Metro for me.

3
00:00:33,233 --> 00:00:34,767
Superintendent rank.

4
00:00:34,800 --> 00:00:35,833
Jake: What do I know
about Metro?

5
00:00:35,867 --> 00:00:37,033
If I've been out of downtown

6
00:00:37,067 --> 00:00:38,167
a half dozen times
the last five years,

7
00:00:38,200 --> 00:00:39,500
it's a lot.

8
00:00:39,533 --> 00:00:41,867
Metro overlaps Boston,
same police power.

9
00:00:41,900 --> 00:00:43,300
Come on Dan,

10
00:00:43,333 --> 00:00:46,033
there must be a dozen captains
begging for that spot.

11
00:00:46,067 --> 00:00:48,133
Last time I checked
I wasn't one of them.

12
00:00:48,167 --> 00:00:49,733
What's the problem?

13
00:00:49,767 --> 00:00:52,900
There's a knot of corruption
in that department so thick

14
00:00:52,933 --> 00:00:55,500
I need a knife to cut it with.

15
00:00:55,533 --> 00:00:58,767
A clean, sharp knife.

16
00:00:58,800 --> 00:01:02,067
We're talking about deep-seated
extensive corruption, Jake,

17
00:01:02,067 --> 00:01:04,300
the kind that takes a
rookie and presses him

18
00:01:04,333 --> 00:01:06,267
into believing if you
wanna be one of the guys,

19
00:01:06,300 --> 00:01:08,167
this is the only way to go.

20
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:10,633
That's why I want
you on the inside.

21
00:01:10,667 --> 00:01:12,533
Bust it up.

22
00:01:12,567 --> 00:01:15,067
Any names in Metro I can use?

23
00:01:15,067 --> 00:01:18,333
I'll need someone. A choirboy.

24
00:01:18,367 --> 00:01:21,333
You're gonna have to
find him for yourself.

25
00:01:21,367 --> 00:01:24,900
How about surveillance?
Wire taps? Backup?

26
00:01:24,933 --> 00:01:28,767
Extremely low
profile, no budget.

27
00:01:28,800 --> 00:01:31,300
No outside agencies.

28
00:01:31,333 --> 00:01:33,433
Thanks a lot, Dan.

29
00:01:41,200 --> 00:01:42,233
(drilling)

30
00:01:53,733 --> 00:01:54,733
(crashing)

31
00:02:06,167 --> 00:02:07,133
(hissing)

32
00:02:26,167 --> 00:02:27,300
(drilling)

33
00:02:43,567 --> 00:02:44,600
(hissing)

34
00:03:06,067 --> 00:03:07,767
(humming)

35
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:09,533
Hey! Looking good, Barry!

36
00:03:09,567 --> 00:03:11,333
Thanks.

37
00:03:11,367 --> 00:03:14,167
So, where's George Washington
gonna put that ax, huh?

38
00:03:14,200 --> 00:03:15,300
Over there? Huh?

39
00:03:15,333 --> 00:03:16,367
(chuckles) Yeah.

40
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:18,500
- (laughs)
- Are you gonna take the car?

41
00:03:18,533 --> 00:03:20,067
Oh, the car...

42
00:03:20,100 --> 00:03:22,067
I'd like to bury that car.

43
00:03:22,067 --> 00:03:23,267
Take the wagon honey.

44
00:03:23,300 --> 00:03:24,867
I wanna check out a
couple more trade-ins

45
00:03:24,900 --> 00:03:26,067
on my way to work.

46
00:03:26,067 --> 00:03:27,633
Mary: Putting
that on the market?

47
00:03:27,667 --> 00:03:30,800
If I can't get my
price I'll work it out.

48
00:03:30,833 --> 00:03:32,067
Right.

49
00:03:36,700 --> 00:03:39,200
(dogs barking)
(birds chirping)

50
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:48,933
Get rid of it for
me, will ya, Frankie?

51
00:03:48,967 --> 00:03:50,200
Thanks a lot, babe.

52
00:03:50,233 --> 00:03:51,367
Burn it, trash it, bury it,

53
00:03:51,400 --> 00:03:52,567
I don't care what
you do just as long

54
00:03:52,600 --> 00:03:55,833
as it looks good
on the insurance.

55
00:03:55,867 --> 00:03:57,467
Wanna get rid
of your car, huh?

56
00:03:57,500 --> 00:03:59,200
Yeah.

57
00:03:59,233 --> 00:04:01,533
We'll take care of it tonight,
no sweat.

58
00:04:01,567 --> 00:04:04,467
But you're better off leaving
these in the ignition.

59
00:04:04,500 --> 00:04:06,467
Park the pig outside
in your usual space,

60
00:04:06,500 --> 00:04:08,800
Doogie and I will swing by
and give it the deep six.

61
00:04:08,833 --> 00:04:10,167
But you're gonna owe me one.

62
00:04:10,200 --> 00:04:12,133
No problem, Frankie.

63
00:04:12,167 --> 00:04:13,700
What are friends for?

64
00:04:13,733 --> 00:04:15,133
Name it.

65
00:04:15,167 --> 00:04:17,500
Well I, uh...

66
00:04:17,533 --> 00:04:19,500
I already got something in mind.

67
00:04:19,533 --> 00:04:22,400
There's this video depot
Doogie and I got cased out.

68
00:04:22,433 --> 00:04:24,133
Medford video depot.

69
00:04:24,167 --> 00:04:26,167
It's ripe for the slaughter.

70
00:04:26,200 --> 00:04:29,767
Frankie, I'm one
of your biggest fans.

71
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:34,867
But I think you're way out
of your league on this depot.

72
00:04:34,900 --> 00:04:37,133
They got a high
tech alarm system.

73
00:04:37,167 --> 00:04:38,500
It's impossible.

74
00:04:38,533 --> 00:04:40,667
Nah, I got an alarm man.

75
00:04:40,700 --> 00:04:42,467
It's the real thing.

76
00:04:42,500 --> 00:04:44,233
Benny Brown. The best in town.

77
00:04:44,267 --> 00:04:45,533
Hey that rhymes!

78
00:04:45,567 --> 00:04:47,800
Maybe we ought to make
an ad for this guy,

79
00:04:47,833 --> 00:04:48,967
what do you think?

80
00:04:49,067 --> 00:04:51,700
Doogie, would
you just shut up?

81
00:04:51,733 --> 00:04:53,867
An alarm man?
Well...

82
00:04:53,900 --> 00:04:56,167
that's a horse of
a different color.

83
00:04:56,200 --> 00:04:57,267
But I gotta run it by Jimmy.

84
00:04:57,300 --> 00:04:58,400
Anything this big in Medford,

85
00:04:58,433 --> 00:05:00,067
I got run it by Jimmy first.

86
00:05:00,067 --> 00:05:01,133
An alarm man?

87
00:05:01,167 --> 00:05:02,633
You got an alarm man and
you're gonna waste him

88
00:05:02,667 --> 00:05:03,767
heisting cameras? Come on!

89
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:06,467
What are you talking
about waste him, huh?

90
00:05:06,500 --> 00:05:10,067
Hey Jimmy you just passed the
video store, stop the car.

91
00:05:10,067 --> 00:05:12,100
That's small potatoes.

92
00:05:12,133 --> 00:05:14,100
You really got an alarm man,

93
00:05:14,133 --> 00:05:15,600
this could be hot!

94
00:05:15,633 --> 00:05:16,967
What are you doin'?

95
00:05:17,067 --> 00:05:19,933
Come on guys, what's goin' on?

96
00:05:19,967 --> 00:05:21,967
Hey guys, huh?

97
00:05:22,067 --> 00:05:24,200
What are you stoppin' here for?

98
00:05:24,233 --> 00:05:25,967
That's my bank.

99
00:05:26,067 --> 00:05:27,433
Frankie: The
Depositor's Trust?

100
00:05:27,467 --> 00:05:29,067
Jimmy: If I'm
lyin', I'm dyin'!

101
00:05:29,067 --> 00:05:31,133
Frankie: (laughs) I get it.

102
00:05:31,167 --> 00:05:33,500
A bank job, right?

103
00:05:33,533 --> 00:05:36,200
What are you talkin' about, huh?
It's nuts!

104
00:05:36,233 --> 00:05:38,567
There's millions in the vault.

105
00:05:38,600 --> 00:05:41,167
That place ought to be a piece
of cake for a real pro.

106
00:05:41,200 --> 00:05:42,333
Tin can.

107
00:05:42,367 --> 00:05:43,700
Hey guys, a video
store's one thing.

108
00:05:43,733 --> 00:05:46,233
We been doing that
kinda heist for years.

109
00:05:46,267 --> 00:05:47,367
But a bank?

110
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:48,567
What's the matter, Frankie?

111
00:05:48,600 --> 00:05:50,067
Afraid of the cops?

112
00:05:50,067 --> 00:05:53,167
(laughter)

113
00:05:53,200 --> 00:05:54,567
(phone rings)

114
00:05:54,600 --> 00:05:57,933
(chatter)
(police scanners)

115
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:06,933
Metro, Clemente, talk to me!

116
00:06:09,467 --> 00:06:11,433
Third and Mason,
Third and Mason,

117
00:06:11,467 --> 00:06:13,067
I can spring a
canine and a cruiser,

118
00:06:13,067 --> 00:06:14,567
but I gotta have
'em back by 11:00,

119
00:06:14,600 --> 00:06:17,100
DUI's up and down the parkway.

120
00:06:17,133 --> 00:06:19,167
Metro, Clemente, talk to me!

121
00:06:19,200 --> 00:06:20,633
Jimmy! How's my boy?

122
00:06:20,667 --> 00:06:22,933
Hey Jerry. Just checking in.

123
00:06:22,967 --> 00:06:25,267
I'm excited about
today's little talk.

124
00:06:25,300 --> 00:06:27,067
Real excited.

125
00:06:27,100 --> 00:06:29,867
That's a big 10-4 but
now's not exactly the time,

126
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:32,200
know what I mean, huh?

127
00:06:32,233 --> 00:06:34,967
(knocking)

128
00:06:35,067 --> 00:06:36,567
I gotta go. Quinn.

129
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:41,500
Spell me, will ya Frank?

130
00:06:41,533 --> 00:06:42,967
Yeah, sure thing Captain.

131
00:06:43,067 --> 00:06:46,900
- (knocking)
- Come in.

132
00:06:46,933 --> 00:06:50,333
Come on, Gerry. Come on in.

133
00:06:50,367 --> 00:06:51,867
Have a seat.

134
00:06:57,900 --> 00:07:01,533
I've gotten word the
mob's running drugs

135
00:07:01,567 --> 00:07:04,233
direct into Logan on
single engine prop planes.

136
00:07:04,267 --> 00:07:06,200
You hear anything?

137
00:07:06,233 --> 00:07:08,067
No, sir.

138
00:07:08,067 --> 00:07:09,767
Narcotics is not
my chain though.

139
00:07:09,800 --> 00:07:11,600
Yeah, I know, I know.

140
00:07:11,633 --> 00:07:14,400
Well, if this running drugs
into the airport is true,

141
00:07:14,433 --> 00:07:17,667
my bet is someone in the
division's on the take.

142
00:07:17,700 --> 00:07:19,200
Nothing makes my skin crawl more

143
00:07:19,233 --> 00:07:21,267
than the stink of a dirty cop.

144
00:07:21,300 --> 00:07:25,300
Hmm, understandable.

145
00:07:25,333 --> 00:07:28,667
Gerry, I'm the
new boy in town.

146
00:07:28,700 --> 00:07:30,900
I'm gonna need all the
help I can get on this.

147
00:07:30,933 --> 00:07:35,667
So, you hear anything about
the division being compromised,

148
00:07:35,700 --> 00:07:37,633
I expect you to come
straight to me, okay?

149
00:07:37,667 --> 00:07:39,767
Of course! Of course.

150
00:07:39,800 --> 00:07:41,600
Well, I gotta be
getting back, sir,

151
00:07:41,633 --> 00:07:43,267
I'm on watch.

152
00:07:43,300 --> 00:07:44,367
Well, go! Go.

153
00:07:44,400 --> 00:07:46,067
Thank you.

154
00:07:46,100 --> 00:07:47,667
Forgive me, Captain Clemente,

155
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:49,433
for I have sinned.

156
00:07:49,467 --> 00:07:50,300
Sir?

157
00:07:50,333 --> 00:07:51,867
Here we are still
on our honeymoon,

158
00:07:51,900 --> 00:07:55,067
and I'm asking you to
break Omertà for me.

159
00:07:55,067 --> 00:07:58,567
That's the second
code of silence!

160
00:07:58,600 --> 00:08:00,367
Is that an Italian joke, sir?

161
00:08:00,400 --> 00:08:02,867
No Ger, it's a cop joke.

162
00:08:02,900 --> 00:08:03,967
Huh.

163
00:08:04,067 --> 00:08:07,067
Not a funny one.

164
00:08:07,100 --> 00:08:08,467
I'll let you know
if I hear anything.

165
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:13,533
Good.

166
00:08:13,567 --> 00:08:22,133
I expect you to.

167
00:08:22,167 --> 00:08:24,667
Oh, no! No, not again!

168
00:08:24,700 --> 00:08:26,233
Where's my car?
Where's my Caddy?

169
00:08:26,267 --> 00:08:27,500
Did you guys see anybody?

170
00:08:27,533 --> 00:08:28,633
Hey, Lieutenant!

171
00:08:28,667 --> 00:08:29,733
Lieutenant!
Get Hawkins from theft.

172
00:08:29,767 --> 00:08:31,067
- Get him up here right now!
- What's the problem?

173
00:08:31,100 --> 00:08:33,300
The problem?
The problem is they stole my car

174
00:08:33,333 --> 00:08:34,467
right out of the squad lot.

175
00:08:34,500 --> 00:08:36,100
Oh, that's a real
shame, Captain.

176
00:08:36,133 --> 00:08:37,433
Why don't you call
the motor pool?

177
00:08:37,467 --> 00:08:38,767
Oh, you're a real comedian.

178
00:08:38,800 --> 00:08:40,867
Everybody's a comedian.

179
00:08:40,900 --> 00:08:42,067
What are you guys
laughing at, huh?

180
00:08:42,100 --> 00:08:47,067
Clemente. What
a piece of work!

181
00:08:47,100 --> 00:08:49,600
Dollars to donuts, he just had
that old rust bucket of his

182
00:08:49,633 --> 00:08:51,367
pinched right off the lot.

183
00:08:51,400 --> 00:08:53,200
(laughter)

184
00:08:53,233 --> 00:08:57,467
What makes you say
that, Lieutenant?

185
00:08:57,500 --> 00:08:59,067
Well, you know Gerry.

186
00:08:59,067 --> 00:09:00,867
Do I?

187
00:09:04,867 --> 00:09:06,067
(revving engine)

188
00:09:06,933 --> 00:09:08,400
(splashing)

189
00:09:10,667 --> 00:09:13,567
If I knew you guys had this
much fun on the job, Frankie,

190
00:09:13,600 --> 00:09:15,667
I would have become
a cop myself.

191
00:09:15,700 --> 00:09:18,367
- Get outta here!
- (laughter)

192
00:09:18,400 --> 00:09:22,300
In this game, making
each shot is important.

193
00:09:22,333 --> 00:09:23,767
Setting up for the next shot

194
00:09:23,800 --> 00:09:30,267
is what it takes to win.

195
00:09:30,300 --> 00:09:32,867
Your wife was very attractive.

196
00:09:32,900 --> 00:09:37,367
Great pool player,
rest her soul.

197
00:09:37,400 --> 00:09:39,233
Speaking of which,

198
00:09:39,267 --> 00:09:41,267
I never knew you were enrolled

199
00:09:41,300 --> 00:09:44,733
at the Jesuit
Seminary, Lieutenant.

200
00:09:44,767 --> 00:09:46,733
That was a long time ago, sir.

201
00:09:46,767 --> 00:09:49,067
Jake.

202
00:09:49,067 --> 00:09:50,467
What do they say?

203
00:09:50,500 --> 00:09:51,867
Give me the boy
until he's seven,

204
00:09:51,900 --> 00:09:53,667
and I'll show you the man?
Something like that.

205
00:09:53,700 --> 00:09:56,167
Yes.

206
00:09:56,200 --> 00:09:58,233
Father killed in action.

207
00:09:58,267 --> 00:10:02,767
Brother on the beat, in Quincy.

208
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:04,833
A regular second
generation Boston cop.

209
00:10:04,867 --> 00:10:06,067
Third.

210
00:10:06,100 --> 00:10:07,967
Third? Whew!

211
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:11,767
You got me beat by one!

212
00:10:11,800 --> 00:10:13,233
So Paul...

213
00:10:13,267 --> 00:10:18,167
what do you know about
Captain Clemente that I don't?

214
00:10:18,200 --> 00:10:20,100
That depends on
what you know, sir.

215
00:10:20,133 --> 00:10:22,133
What I know?

216
00:10:22,167 --> 00:10:26,167
Omertà from a Jesuit?

217
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:27,233
Silence among thieves,

218
00:10:27,267 --> 00:10:29,767
even if the thieves are cops?

219
00:10:29,800 --> 00:10:32,567
Mea culpa, padre.

220
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:48,700
I think I can trust you, Paul.

221
00:10:48,733 --> 00:10:52,767
So here's what I know.

222
00:10:52,800 --> 00:10:54,267
I've been doing a
little nosing around.

223
00:10:54,300 --> 00:10:59,333
Rumor has it that Clemente
is a legend in his own time.

224
00:10:59,367 --> 00:11:03,633
Pulling patrol heists, TVs,

225
00:11:03,667 --> 00:11:06,733
refrigerators, washer-dryers.

226
00:11:06,767 --> 00:11:09,267
Presents for his wife, his kid.

227
00:11:09,300 --> 00:11:12,400
Probably some other
officers involved.

228
00:11:12,433 --> 00:11:14,700
But who's gonna talk
about that, huh?

229
00:11:14,733 --> 00:11:17,767
Omertà?

230
00:11:17,800 --> 00:11:19,267
You know a lot
about him then, sir.

231
00:11:19,300 --> 00:11:21,400
I know I hate everything
that he stands for,

232
00:11:21,433 --> 00:11:23,100
ever since I put on a badge.

233
00:11:23,133 --> 00:11:24,400
Why don't you
take him down then?

234
00:11:24,433 --> 00:11:26,200
I can't take him down because

235
00:11:26,233 --> 00:11:29,233
I haven't got anything
hard against him.

236
00:11:29,267 --> 00:11:30,600
Except what?

237
00:11:30,633 --> 00:11:33,233
Beating his electric meter?

238
00:11:33,267 --> 00:11:35,933
I heard that one.

239
00:11:35,967 --> 00:11:37,900
But when it was tipped
he busted up his box

240
00:11:37,933 --> 00:11:40,633
and said burglars broke into it.

241
00:11:40,667 --> 00:11:45,100
So the choirboy can sing,
if he hears the right tune.

242
00:11:45,133 --> 00:11:47,533
Gerry's dirty as sin.

243
00:11:47,567 --> 00:11:50,733
He's the highest ranking
man in my department.

244
00:11:50,767 --> 00:11:55,067
And it burns me I haven't got
anything hard against him.

245
00:11:55,100 --> 00:11:56,700
This whole part of
town is compromised,

246
00:11:56,733 --> 00:11:58,467
not just by OC,

247
00:11:58,500 --> 00:12:00,467
but by cops pulling
their own scams

248
00:12:00,500 --> 00:12:03,467
with or without the mob.

249
00:12:03,500 --> 00:12:06,500
He's the worst
part of that breed.

250
00:12:06,533 --> 00:12:11,067
If I can bring him down,
it's gonna make an example.

251
00:12:11,100 --> 00:12:18,433
Are you with me?

252
00:12:18,467 --> 00:12:21,500
Or does being a cop
mean nothing to you?

253
00:12:21,533 --> 00:12:22,500
That's what it comes down to,

254
00:12:22,533 --> 00:12:24,400
nothing less than that.

255
00:12:24,433 --> 00:12:28,467
People trust cops.
They ought to trust cops.

256
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:30,500
Anything gets in the
way of that trust,

257
00:12:30,533 --> 00:12:32,533
I'm gonna smash.

258
00:12:32,567 --> 00:12:35,567
Now once again, are you with me,

259
00:12:35,600 --> 00:12:39,900
Lieutenant?

260
00:12:39,933 --> 00:12:41,633
I'm with you, sir, yes.

261
00:12:41,667 --> 00:12:44,200
Good.

262
00:12:44,233 --> 00:12:48,633
Now.

263
00:12:48,667 --> 00:12:55,500
What do you know about
Gerry that I don't?

264
00:12:55,533 --> 00:12:56,667
There's this girl.

265
00:12:56,700 --> 00:12:57,767
What girl?

266
00:12:57,800 --> 00:12:59,333
Kelly Sherwood.

267
00:12:59,367 --> 00:13:02,867
Gerry's mistress, going
on at least three years.

268
00:13:02,900 --> 00:13:04,900
She works bails in Revere.

269
00:13:04,933 --> 00:13:07,633
I've seen his car parked outside
her house plenty of times.

270
00:13:07,667 --> 00:13:10,500
- On duty?
- Most of the time.

271
00:13:10,533 --> 00:13:14,400
And what's so important that
it can't wait another hour?

272
00:13:14,433 --> 00:13:16,800
Call of duty, baby.

273
00:13:16,833 --> 00:13:20,600
Well just as long as it's
not the call of the wild.

274
00:13:20,633 --> 00:13:22,333
Better not be going out on me,

275
00:13:22,367 --> 00:13:24,100
or home to Mary.

276
00:13:24,133 --> 00:13:26,100
(Gerry sighs)

277
00:13:26,133 --> 00:13:27,567
Know what the
problem with you is?

278
00:13:27,600 --> 00:13:29,700
Hmm?

279
00:13:29,733 --> 00:13:31,600
You have no
respect for the law.

280
00:13:31,633 --> 00:13:35,333
(Kelly laughs)

281
00:13:35,367 --> 00:13:36,500
Oh, and you do?

282
00:13:36,533 --> 00:13:38,733
You bet. Gotta go.

283
00:13:38,767 --> 00:13:39,867
Oh come on baby, stay!

284
00:13:39,900 --> 00:13:41,200
- Baby...
- Kelly: Come on!

285
00:13:54,967 --> 00:13:56,467
(screeching tires)

286
00:14:10,200 --> 00:14:11,333
Busting into a bank with cops,

287
00:14:11,367 --> 00:14:12,800
I mean that'd be history,

288
00:14:12,833 --> 00:14:14,233
it'd be a first.

289
00:14:14,267 --> 00:14:16,300
So what's the problem, Benny?

290
00:14:16,333 --> 00:14:18,167
You're the problem, Captain.

291
00:14:18,200 --> 00:14:19,433
You and the two sergeants here.

292
00:14:19,467 --> 00:14:21,467
I mean how do I know
that this isn't a setup?

293
00:14:21,500 --> 00:14:23,767
That wouldn't fly,
Benny me boy!

294
00:14:23,800 --> 00:14:25,600
It's entrapment.

295
00:14:25,633 --> 00:14:27,667
Entrapment nothin', I'm
talkin' about gettin' whacked.

296
00:14:27,700 --> 00:14:29,400
No.

297
00:14:29,433 --> 00:14:30,933
Cops or no cops,

298
00:14:30,967 --> 00:14:32,500
an alarm man is always
lookin' over his shoulder

299
00:14:32,533 --> 00:14:34,100
after the job.

300
00:14:34,133 --> 00:14:37,500
Lone outsider brought in to
help the tight local boys.

301
00:14:37,533 --> 00:14:38,733
And the local boys being cops,

302
00:14:38,767 --> 00:14:41,433
well I figure the odds of me
being hit are about even money.

303
00:14:41,467 --> 00:14:45,800
Not that we'd do that, Benny.

304
00:14:45,833 --> 00:14:47,333
Yeah. Besides,

305
00:14:47,367 --> 00:14:49,167
any bank job it's risky enough.

306
00:14:49,200 --> 00:14:50,433
Risky?

307
00:14:50,467 --> 00:14:51,700
This place is a tin can!

308
00:14:51,733 --> 00:14:54,367
There's millions just waiting.

309
00:14:54,400 --> 00:14:56,367
I've been prayin' for years

310
00:14:56,400 --> 00:15:00,433
for someone like
you to come along.

311
00:15:00,467 --> 00:15:01,767
Let me tell ya
how a guy like me

312
00:15:01,800 --> 00:15:04,833
lives long enough
to be a guy like me.

313
00:15:04,867 --> 00:15:08,433
You stay as far away
as possible from cops.

314
00:15:08,467 --> 00:15:11,300
Sounds like you gotta
learn to trust cops, Benny.

315
00:15:11,333 --> 00:15:14,467
Cops like us could
be your best friends.

316
00:15:14,500 --> 00:15:16,100
Why should I trust you?

317
00:15:16,133 --> 00:15:18,100
Because, Benny, there
are two kinds of cops.

318
00:15:18,133 --> 00:15:19,867
There are honest cops,
and there are smart cops,

319
00:15:19,900 --> 00:15:23,700
and even the honest
cops don't talk.

320
00:15:23,733 --> 00:15:30,633
It's a perfect little
world out there, Benny.

321
00:15:30,667 --> 00:15:33,833
Okay. Let's just say
that I do trust ya.

322
00:15:33,867 --> 00:15:37,933
(laughs) I mean I'm not
so sure that I can still

323
00:15:37,967 --> 00:15:39,800
take this bank down.

324
00:15:39,833 --> 00:15:41,567
Here's my proposal.

325
00:15:41,600 --> 00:15:43,867
Just check the joint out,

326
00:15:43,900 --> 00:15:46,667
and then you make your decision.

327
00:15:46,700 --> 00:15:48,067
If it ain't
everything Jimmy says,

328
00:15:48,067 --> 00:15:49,233
you can jump off the wagon,

329
00:15:49,267 --> 00:15:52,800
no harm no foul.

330
00:15:52,833 --> 00:15:54,167
Ah, you're a smart guy, Gerry,

331
00:15:54,200 --> 00:15:58,567
just like they say.

332
00:15:58,600 --> 00:16:00,400
(sighs) Okay, Captain,

333
00:16:00,433 --> 00:16:02,800
so when can I see
this here tin can?

334
00:16:02,833 --> 00:16:04,200
Jimmy: Tonight.

335
00:16:34,833 --> 00:16:36,700
It's popcorn, a piece of cake.

336
00:16:36,733 --> 00:16:38,733
Absolutely unbelievable!

337
00:16:38,767 --> 00:16:40,400
Benny's in, even splits.

338
00:16:40,433 --> 00:16:42,300
- It's an old box.
- All right.

339
00:16:42,333 --> 00:16:44,633
Hell of a lot of telephone
wires in there with alarm

340
00:16:44,667 --> 00:16:46,533
but nothin' electrical!

341
00:16:46,567 --> 00:16:48,333
How soon before
you can make it?

342
00:16:48,367 --> 00:16:49,867
Can you get me
in an hour a shot,

343
00:16:49,900 --> 00:16:51,767
say three times a week?

344
00:16:51,800 --> 00:16:53,367
- Yeah.
- A month.

345
00:16:53,400 --> 00:16:55,567
Two at the most
to beat the alarm.

346
00:16:55,600 --> 00:16:57,133
Another week to
build a bypass box

347
00:16:57,167 --> 00:16:58,667
so we can control it.

348
00:16:58,700 --> 00:17:00,933
But, I need an inside man.

349
00:17:00,967 --> 00:17:02,067
I need a blaster.

350
00:17:02,100 --> 00:17:03,167
Come on, Benny!

351
00:17:03,200 --> 00:17:04,867
Another guy to split the take?

352
00:17:04,900 --> 00:17:08,767
Yeah, well I need
someone to blow that vault.

353
00:17:08,800 --> 00:17:12,067
We don't beat the
vault, we get nothin'.

354
00:17:12,100 --> 00:17:13,533
Look, I'm tight with a demo man,

355
00:17:13,567 --> 00:17:16,267
Vince Brogan. He's a pro.

356
00:17:16,300 --> 00:17:17,400
A pro that'll watch your back

357
00:17:17,433 --> 00:17:19,167
against us cops, huh Benny?

358
00:17:19,200 --> 00:17:22,067
You're reading my mind.

359
00:17:22,100 --> 00:17:23,600
Sure okay, maybe one of my own

360
00:17:23,633 --> 00:17:25,533
will make me feel a
little more comfortable.

361
00:17:25,567 --> 00:17:29,467
But I do need a
blaster, that's no lie.

362
00:17:29,500 --> 00:17:34,067
No Brogan, no Benny.

363
00:17:34,067 --> 00:17:35,500
Welcome aboard, Benny.

364
00:17:35,533 --> 00:17:38,367
(laughs)

365
00:17:38,400 --> 00:17:40,233
If I'm lyin' I'm dyin'!

366
00:17:40,267 --> 00:17:42,333
We're going scuba fishing
off the boat tomorrow.

367
00:17:42,367 --> 00:17:43,933
You and Quinn?

368
00:17:43,967 --> 00:17:45,733
He says he's never
done it before,

369
00:17:45,767 --> 00:17:47,700
and he wants to build up
his retirement skills.

370
00:17:47,733 --> 00:17:50,667
(laughs) You and Quinn!

371
00:17:50,700 --> 00:17:53,100
That's something
I never figured.

372
00:17:53,133 --> 00:17:54,667
Especially now.

373
00:17:54,700 --> 00:17:58,067
You think he's on to the bank?

374
00:17:58,100 --> 00:18:00,067
Ah, come on!

375
00:18:00,067 --> 00:18:01,800
Don't even fool,

376
00:18:01,833 --> 00:18:03,833
don't even go in that area.

377
00:18:03,867 --> 00:18:06,100
Quinn in a scuba
suit! (laughs)

378
00:18:06,133 --> 00:18:09,233
Like a beached whale!
That's a picture!

379
00:18:09,267 --> 00:18:10,533
I'm about to wet my pants!

380
00:18:10,567 --> 00:18:17,133
I gotta hit the head.

381
00:18:17,167 --> 00:18:19,367
Hey Scarzi, what do you say?

382
00:18:19,400 --> 00:18:20,667
Hey, Ger!

383
00:18:20,700 --> 00:18:24,667
Hey, Mr. Scarzi!

384
00:18:24,700 --> 00:18:26,067
Got the same show this week.

385
00:18:26,100 --> 00:18:28,100
What happened, Nick?
Sinatra cancelled again?

386
00:18:28,133 --> 00:18:29,533
Sinatra? Very funny.

387
00:18:29,567 --> 00:18:31,367
(Gerry laughs)

388
00:18:31,400 --> 00:18:33,633
Look, I need some help.

389
00:18:33,667 --> 00:18:34,933
You got a second?

390
00:18:34,967 --> 00:18:36,133
For an old friend
and choirboy?

391
00:18:36,167 --> 00:18:37,700
Yeah. Sit down.

392
00:18:37,733 --> 00:18:38,700
Thank you.

393
00:18:38,733 --> 00:18:40,433
What's up?

394
00:18:40,467 --> 00:18:42,100
Well I got some
trouble, you know?

395
00:18:42,133 --> 00:18:44,067
There's these two guys,

396
00:18:44,067 --> 00:18:46,067
dealers, pals of mine.

397
00:18:46,067 --> 00:18:48,833
They got pinched by
Metro over at Wellington.

398
00:18:48,867 --> 00:18:50,200
They're connected, you know?

399
00:18:50,233 --> 00:18:51,567
Yeah.

400
00:18:51,600 --> 00:18:53,633
Well, Ferrano
wants 'em cut loose.

401
00:18:53,667 --> 00:18:55,700
(laughs) Nick!

402
00:18:55,733 --> 00:18:57,500
I mean listen, this is his turf,

403
00:18:57,533 --> 00:18:59,800
we're tight and all that
happy horse manure over there,

404
00:18:59,833 --> 00:19:03,200
but even he knows
I can't erase a drug bust!

405
00:19:03,233 --> 00:19:05,867
I just want you to talk
to the arresting officer.

406
00:19:05,900 --> 00:19:07,900
He's an undercover guy.

407
00:19:07,933 --> 00:19:09,200
Bobby Kellogg, you know,

408
00:19:09,233 --> 00:19:10,433
just get him to stretch things

409
00:19:10,467 --> 00:19:13,267
so that these two
guys can get off.

410
00:19:13,300 --> 00:19:16,733
Say that the bust was illegal.

411
00:19:16,767 --> 00:19:20,267
Just talk to him, okay?

412
00:19:20,300 --> 00:19:23,533
(distant sirens)

413
00:19:23,567 --> 00:19:25,533
Hey Kellogg, you got a second?

414
00:19:25,567 --> 00:19:27,900
Captain? What's the occasion?

415
00:19:27,933 --> 00:19:30,133
Ah, you gotta help me out
on something here, Bobby.

416
00:19:30,167 --> 00:19:31,700
Yeah, sure, what?

417
00:19:31,733 --> 00:19:33,500
That bust you made down
on Wellington yesterday.

418
00:19:33,533 --> 00:19:35,733
Oldham and Willette?

419
00:19:35,767 --> 00:19:37,100
Did you get 'em clean?

420
00:19:37,133 --> 00:19:38,967
Yeah. Clean as a cat's tongue.

421
00:19:39,067 --> 00:19:40,233
Big haul, too.

422
00:19:40,267 --> 00:19:42,500
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

423
00:19:42,533 --> 00:19:44,067
So who wants to know? Lawyers?

424
00:19:44,100 --> 00:19:45,467
Eh, a friend of a friend.

425
00:19:45,500 --> 00:19:46,833
Owns a nightclub
down on Route 1.

426
00:19:46,867 --> 00:19:48,400
Real connected.

427
00:19:48,433 --> 00:19:50,167
Anyway, he wanted me
to pass it on to you,

428
00:19:50,200 --> 00:19:54,700
that there's a lot of real
money to be made here.

429
00:19:54,733 --> 00:19:59,100
With the right kind of truth.

430
00:19:59,133 --> 00:20:00,967
I spoke to Kellogg, like I said.

431
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:04,533
Wasn't too subtle,
but he got the hint.

432
00:20:04,567 --> 00:20:06,567
No.

433
00:20:06,600 --> 00:20:07,933
What do you want from me?

434
00:20:07,967 --> 00:20:09,367
This is no good.

435
00:20:09,400 --> 00:20:12,567
I got guys to account to
if those two guys go down.

436
00:20:12,600 --> 00:20:13,600
Gerry: If they go down, 
 they go down.

437
00:20:13,633 --> 00:20:14,900
It happens, okay?

438
00:20:14,933 --> 00:20:16,733
They're small fry,
don't worry about it.

439
00:20:16,767 --> 00:20:18,867
Kellogg's a square,
he won't bite.

440
00:20:18,900 --> 00:20:20,667
Scarzi: Can't you talk 
 to him again?

441
00:20:20,700 --> 00:20:21,867
No way!

442
00:20:21,900 --> 00:20:23,300
What the hell's the
matter with you man?

443
00:20:23,333 --> 00:20:25,367
Come on!
Stop giving me this grief!

444
00:20:25,400 --> 00:20:27,000
Leave me alone,
I'm gonna go fishing.

445
00:20:27,033 --> 00:20:28,867
Jake: Ah, last time
I was on a boat,

446
00:20:28,900 --> 00:20:31,167
I don't even remember.

447
00:20:31,200 --> 00:20:32,800
I ought to enjoy life more.

448
00:20:32,833 --> 00:20:37,833
(laughs) That's right.
That's what it's for!

449
00:20:37,867 --> 00:20:40,600
Hmm, right, right.

450
00:20:40,633 --> 00:20:43,367
Maybe I'll get me a boat.

451
00:20:43,400 --> 00:20:45,033
There you go.

452
00:20:45,067 --> 00:20:46,867
How much does
this run you, Gerry?

453
00:20:46,900 --> 00:20:49,133
(Gerry whistles)

454
00:20:49,167 --> 00:20:51,600
Well, you know what
they say about a boat.

455
00:20:51,633 --> 00:20:52,700
I don't know, Jake,

456
00:20:52,733 --> 00:20:54,200
what do they say about a boat?

457
00:20:54,233 --> 00:20:56,467
It's a hole in the water
you throw money into.

458
00:20:56,500 --> 00:20:58,167
(Gerry chuckles)

459
00:20:58,200 --> 00:20:59,433
What's the sense of having money

460
00:20:59,467 --> 00:21:01,200
if you don't spend it, right?

461
00:21:01,233 --> 00:21:03,467
Except if you don't have it!

462
00:21:03,500 --> 00:21:06,300
And that's a horse
of a different color.

463
00:21:06,333 --> 00:21:07,367
Yeah, I tell ya,

464
00:21:07,400 --> 00:21:11,200
this baby keeps me skimpin'
all the way around.

465
00:21:11,233 --> 00:21:13,433
Boston cops.

466
00:21:13,467 --> 00:21:15,467
To Boston cops.

467
00:21:15,500 --> 00:21:17,333
We always get our man.

468
00:21:17,367 --> 00:21:20,833
Oh, those are the
Mounties, Jake.

469
00:21:20,867 --> 00:21:24,267
My mistake!

470
00:21:24,300 --> 00:21:26,600
What do Boston cops get, Gerry?

471
00:21:26,633 --> 00:21:29,467
Twenty-two thousand
dollars a year (laughs).

472
00:21:29,500 --> 00:21:31,533
Good one!

473
00:21:31,567 --> 00:21:33,633
To Boston cops.

474
00:21:33,667 --> 00:21:35,467
The best cops in the world.

475
00:21:35,500 --> 00:21:36,900
Best in the world.

476
00:21:43,767 --> 00:21:45,800
And the outside lock to
the optical shop is easy.

477
00:21:45,833 --> 00:21:48,333
I picked it last night
when I was on patrol.

478
00:21:48,367 --> 00:21:50,867
Gerry: Went in, looked around. 
 It was beautiful.

479
00:21:50,900 --> 00:21:52,933
The loft's got a dual 
 set of heavy-duty sockets

480
00:21:52,967 --> 00:21:54,200
for grinding lenses,

481
00:21:54,233 --> 00:21:55,833
which is right near
the wall to the bank.

482
00:21:55,867 --> 00:21:57,633
Now, that's perfect because 
 there's plenty enough juice

483
00:21:57,667 --> 00:21:59,767
to handle the drills to
get us through the wall

484
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:01,567
into the crawl space,

485
00:22:01,600 --> 00:22:03,300
over the vault.

486
00:22:05,633 --> 00:22:07,967
The vault.

487
00:22:08,067 --> 00:22:09,400
I don't know.

488
00:22:09,433 --> 00:22:10,967
Vince?

489
00:22:11,067 --> 00:22:12,300
It's an old baby

490
00:22:12,333 --> 00:22:14,567
with metal rods
crisscrossing the top,

491
00:22:14,600 --> 00:22:15,700
should make it easier on us,

492
00:22:15,733 --> 00:22:17,067
but nothing's a cinch.

493
00:22:17,067 --> 00:22:18,600
We'll drill a couple of holes,

494
00:22:18,633 --> 00:22:20,433
smash through with
sledgehammers.

495
00:22:20,467 --> 00:22:23,933
That doesn't work,
we use dynamite.

496
00:22:23,967 --> 00:22:27,933
(laughs) Dynamite, huh?

497
00:22:27,967 --> 00:22:30,067
- Yeah.
- What are you, nuts?

498
00:22:30,067 --> 00:22:32,300
No.

499
00:22:32,333 --> 00:22:33,733
Somebody's gonna hear us.

500
00:22:33,767 --> 00:22:35,967
We'll use a couple of
sandbags to muffle the sound.

501
00:22:36,067 --> 00:22:37,767
Yeah, sure.

502
00:22:37,800 --> 00:22:38,967
Listen, I'd like
three nights in there

503
00:22:39,067 --> 00:22:40,400
over a long weekend.
You know?

504
00:22:40,433 --> 00:22:41,967
Short hits in and out,

505
00:22:42,067 --> 00:22:43,900
it's worth it to
clean all the boxes.

506
00:22:43,933 --> 00:22:47,567
Like some satin sheets
while you're at it?

507
00:22:47,600 --> 00:22:50,400
Three nights.

508
00:22:50,433 --> 00:22:57,133
Shouldn't be difficult.

509
00:22:57,167 --> 00:23:00,300
Memorial Day weekend.

510
00:23:00,333 --> 00:23:04,067
(suspense music)

511
00:23:24,967 --> 00:23:27,700
Got the name of a
pal Gerry hangs with.

512
00:23:27,733 --> 00:23:29,200
Hunting, fishing,

513
00:23:29,233 --> 00:23:30,733
families go out together.

514
00:23:30,767 --> 00:23:32,367
Everybody knows they're friends,

515
00:23:32,400 --> 00:23:33,933
but it could go deeper.

516
00:23:33,967 --> 00:23:35,633
The guy's a sergeant
over in Medford.

517
00:23:35,667 --> 00:23:36,967
Jimmy Donnelly?

518
00:23:37,067 --> 00:23:38,633
You know the name?

519
00:23:38,667 --> 00:23:40,067
Why don't you give it to me?

520
00:23:40,067 --> 00:23:41,533
I just heard rumors, Jake!

521
00:23:41,567 --> 00:23:42,933
I'm not gonna trash
a cop on a rumor,

522
00:23:42,967 --> 00:23:46,133
not to you or anybody!

523
00:23:46,167 --> 00:23:48,400
It's probably a
dead end anyway.

524
00:23:48,433 --> 00:23:49,500
Clemente and Donnelly

525
00:23:49,533 --> 00:23:51,133
are pulling penny ante
stuff together,

526
00:23:51,167 --> 00:23:52,967
fat chance of proving it.

527
00:23:53,067 --> 00:23:54,067
Omertà.

528
00:23:54,100 --> 00:23:55,967
Right. Cops don't rat on cops.

529
00:23:56,067 --> 00:23:57,933
Even Jesuit cops!

530
00:23:57,967 --> 00:24:02,100
